pe, you can’t assign a reference for a different set of arguments.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating method accessibility**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether it's acceptable to call a synthetic public method in my tests. The instructions say not to use reflection directly unless the public API requires it. Since the public API's loadPlugin is inline reified and unreachable from Kotlin, I'm considering using the public API of mockk instead for explicit loading. It seems like I might not need to cover the default synthetic method after all.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_dwkF0wm3f8XDZQSVBNxVcsCV|fc_087957684410c0260169fad93e8130819c8318534d986cae9c", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.mockk/mockk-jvm/1.14.9/user-code-filter.json"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 769, "output": 1260, "cacheRead": 35840, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 37869, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778047273105, "responseId": "resp_087957684410c0260169fad9299c54819c9596c684537cea56"}}
